  "opinion": "As a retired woman with a bachelor’s degree who grew up in a time when STEM fields were often seen as the domain of men, I’ve witnessed firsthand how stereotype threat can undermine potential. Stereotype threat occurs when individuals internalize negative beliefs about their group’s abilities, leading to anxiety that hinders performance. In my community, this was evident when my son, a bright young man with a passion for engineering, felt discouraged after a high school project was dismissed by a teacher who assumed he wasn’t ‘the type’ to handle complex math. It’s a quiet but powerful force that can make students question their own capabilities, especially in fields where they don’t see themselves represented. Addressing this isn’t just about changing policies—it’s about fostering environments where every child feels valued. I’ve seen through my hobbies, like running and cinema, how confidence and belonging are built through positive reinforcement. Schools should integrate mentorship programs that pair students with professionals who share their backgrounds, and teachers must be trained to recognize and counteract unconscious biases. The key is to create spaces where students feel safe to fail without judgment. As someone who values community and empathy, I believe this work is essential. It’s not about fixing individuals but about transforming the culture around learning. In a world that often tells young people they don’t belong, we must actively challenge those narratives to ensure everyone has the opportunity to thrive.",
